\begin{framed}

\noindent \textbf{Abstract} \\

Human Adenovirus sequencing data provide valuable information about viral evolution, genome diversity, and strain relationships. In this project, we intend to provide a reproducible Snakemake workflow designed for the analysis of Human Adenovirus sequencing datasets. The workflow will integrate quality control, read preprocessing, genome assembly, phylogenetic reconstruction, and genomic variability analysis into a modular and portable bioinformatics pipeline. Existing Snakemake wrappers will be used whenever available in order to improve reproducibility and portability, while Conda environments will be employed for tools without wrappers.

The workflow will generate assembled viral genomes in FASTA format, phylogenetic trees in Newick format together with graphical visualizations, and genomic variability profiles computed using high-resolution per base variability as well as overlapping sliding windows of configurable size. We may choose either de novo or reference-based assembly strategies which are to be discussed and compared with respect to assembly bias, reproducibility, and suitability for downstream phylogenetic inference.

The workflow will be implemented using Snakemake, Conda environments, configuration files, and modular rule definitions to ensure portability across computational environments and reproducible execution on local systems as well as HPC infrastructures.

\end{framed}

