\section{Introduction}

Human Adenoviruses are double-stranded DNA viruses associated with respiratory, gastrointestinal, and ocular infections \cite{Lion2014}. Due to their medical relevance and genetic diversity, sequencing-based analysis of Adenovirus genomes is important for epidemiological studies, evolutionary analysis, and outbreak investigation.

Modern sequencing technologies generate large amounts of short-read data that require systematic computational analysis. Such analyses typically involve quality assessment, preprocessing, genome assembly, sequence comparison, phylogenetic reconstruction, and variability analysis. Performing these tasks manually is error-prone and difficult to reproduce. Therefore, workflow management systems such as Snakemake are increasingly used to automate and standardize bioinformatics pipelines \cite{Koster2012}.

The goal of this project is to design and implement a reproducible Snakemake workflow for the analysis of Human Adenovirus sequencing data. The workflow aims to:

\begin{itemize}
    \item generate assembled viral genomes,
    \item reconstruct phylogenetic relationships between strains,
    \item identify regions of high and low genomic variability,
    \item provide reproducible and portable workflow execution.
\end{itemize}

In addition to workflow implementation, methodological design choices are discussed, including the comparison between de novo and reference-based assembly strategies and the definition of genomic variability metrics.

