\subsection{Quality Control and Read Preprocessing}

Initial quality control will be performed using FastQC in order to assess sequencing quality, adapter contamination, GC content, sequence duplication levels, and per-base quality scores \cite{Andrews2010}. MultiQC will be used to aggregate FastQC reports into a single summary report \cite{Ewels2016}.

As an alternative to Trimmomatic \cite{Bolger2014} used in the previous assignment, the workflow will employ \texttt{fastp} for read preprocessing. Fastp is a modern and efficient preprocessing tool that integrates quality filtering, adapter trimming, quality correction, and quality reporting in a single application \cite{Chen2018}. Compared to Trimmomatic, fastp offers improved execution speed, integrated HTML reporting, and simplified parameter handling.

Lastly we will substract host DNA contanimation in our samples by aligning reads against the host (human) genome and remove any reads that map to the host using Bowtie2. 

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\subsection{Genome Assembly Strategy}

A central design decision concerns the choice between de novo assembly and reference-based assembly. In order to assess which strategy to employ we will take a representative subset of sequences across all strains and map to an existing adenovirus reference. If the mapping yields a high proportion of unmapped reads, low genome coverage, or lots of false SNP's, we will move forward with De Novo assembly. Otherwise we will do a reference-based assembly. 

\subsubsection{De Novo Assembly}

De novo assembly reconstructs genomes directly from sequencing reads without relying on a reference genome. In this workflow, SPAdes will be selected as the de novo assembler due to its strong performance on microbial and viral sequencing datasets \cite{Bankevich2012}.

Advantages of de novo assembly include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item reduced reference bias,
    \item ability to detect structural variation,
    \item suitability for divergent or unknown strains.
\end{itemize}

However, de novo assembly may produce fragmented assemblies in regions of low coverage or repetitive genomic structure.

\subsubsection{Reference-Based Assembly}

Reference-based assembly aligns sequencing reads against an existing reference genome and generates a consensus sequence. In this workflow, BWA-MEM2 \cite{Vasimuddin2019} was selected as a modern alternative to Bowtie2.

Advantages of reference-based assembly include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item improved assembly continuity,
    \item computational efficiency,
    \item robust reconstruction for closely related strains.
\end{itemize}

A major limitation is reference bias, where genomic regions differing strongly from the reference may be incorrectly reconstructed or missed entirely.

\subsubsection{Assembly Quality Control}

Quality assessment of the assembled viral genomes will be performed in order to evaluate assembly completeness and reliability before downstream phylogenetic and variability analyses are conducted.

For de novo assemblies generated with SPAdes, assembly statistics such as contig number, total assembly length, N50 values, and GC content will be evaluated using QUAST. QUAST provides standardized assembly quality metrics and facilitates comparison between reconstructed genomes \cite{Gurevich2013}.

For reference-based assemblies, mapping statistics and alignment quality metrics will additionally be assessed using samtools and Qualimap2 \cite{Danecek2021,Okonechnikov2016}. These analyses will provide information regarding sequencing depth, genome coverage, mapping quality, and potential low-confidence genomic regions.

Assembly quality control is particularly important because assembly artifacts or incomplete genome reconstruction may influence downstream phylogenetic inference and genomic variability estimation.
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\subsection{Multiple Sequence Alignment}

After assembly, all reconstructed genomes will be combined into a single FASTA file and aligned using MAFFT \cite{Katoh2013}. Multiple sequence alignment is required before phylogenetic reconstruction and genomic variability analysis.

MAFFT was selected because it provides:

\begin{itemize}
    \item high alignment accuracy,
    \item efficient execution,
    \item robust performance for viral genome datasets.
\end{itemize}

The resulting alignment is stored in FASTA format and used for all downstream comparative analyses.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\subsection{Phylogenetic Reconstruction}

Phylogenetic relationships between assembled viral genomes will be reconstructed using IQ-TREE. The workflow will generate:

\begin{itemize}
    \item a phylogenetic tree in Newick format,
    \item graphical visualization in PDF or PNG format.
\end{itemize}

Phylogenetic analysis enables identification of closely related strains and provides insight into the evolutionary relationships among sequenced Adenovirus samples.

IQ-TREE \cite{Nguyen2015} will be selected because it supports:

\begin{itemize}
    \item fast maximum-likelihood tree inference,
    \item automated model selection,
    \item statistical branch support estimation.
\end{itemize}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\subsection{Genomic Variability Analysis}

An important objective of the workflow is the identification of genomic regions exhibiting high or low sequence variability.

Two complementary variability approaches will be considered:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item per-position variability,
    \item sliding-window variability.
\end{enumerate}

Per-position variability provides high-resolution information for individual nucleotide positions. However, this approach may produce noisy signals that are difficult to interpret biologically.

Therefore, an overlapping sliding-window strategy will be additionally implemented. For each window of length \(x\), the average variability across all positions within the window will be computed. Consecutive windows overlap in order to obtain smoother and more continuous variability profiles.

The window size is going to be implemented as a configurable workflow parameter in \texttt{config.yaml}, allowing users to adjust the resolution of the analysis.

The workflow will generate:

\begin{itemize}
    \item a text file containing variability values for all windows,
    \item a plot showing variability across genomic coordinates.
\end{itemize}

