\section{Discussion}

The designed workflow combines modern bioinformatics tools within a reproducible Snakemake framework for the analysis of Human Adenovirus sequencing data.

One important methodological consideration is choosing an assembly strategy. Reference-based assembly may artificially increase similarity to the reference genome, while de novo assembly may introduce fragmentation or assembly artifacts. Preliminarily mapping to an existing reference helps to see which method is appropriate for the dataset at hand. 

Another important consideration concerns genomic variability analysis. Small sliding windows provide high spatial resolution but may generate noisy signals, whereas large windows produce smoother variability profiles at the expense of local detail. Overlapping windows provide a compromise between these two extremes.

Future extensions of the workflow could include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item variant calling,
    \item recombination analysis,
    \item automated tree annotation,
    \item support for long-read sequencing technologies.
\end{itemize}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\section{Conclusion}

In this project, a reproducible Snakemake workflow will be designed for Human Adenovirus genome analysis. The workflow integrates quality control, preprocessing, genome assembly, phylogenetic reconstruction, and genomic variability analysis into a modular and portable pipeline.

Modern bioinformatics tools including FastQC, fastp, SPAdes, BWA-MEM2, MAFFT, and IQ-TREE were selected in order to provide efficient and reproducible workflow execution. The workflow supports both de novo and reference-based assembly strategies and enables investigation of sequence variability using overlapping sliding-window analysis.

Overall, the workflow provides a flexible and reproducible framework for viral genome analysis and demonstrates how Snakemake can be used to organize complex bioinformatics analyses in a scalable and portable manner.

